04579nam a22005415i 9780226410968DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20172017ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2013016561  a97802264109687 a10.7208/97802264109682doi  a(DE-B1597)550105  a(OCoLC)980818459  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aHV8698b.D4713 2014 4aHV8698b.D4713 2017 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a364.6601223  aCI 56012rvk0(DE-625)rvk/18485:117711 aDerrida, Jacques, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Death Penalty, Volume II /cJacques Derrida. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Seminars of Jacques Derrida00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword to the English Edition -- tGeneral Introduction to the French Edition -- tEditorial Note -- tTranslator’s Acknowledgments -- tFirst Session. December 6, 2000 -- tSecond Session. December 13, 2000 -- tThird session. January 10, 2001 -- tFourth session. January 31, 2001 -- tFifth session. February 7, 2001 -- tSixth session. February 21, 2001 -- tSeventh session. February 28, 2001 -- tEighth session. March 7, 2001 -- tNinth session. March 21, 2001 -- tTenth session. March 28, 2001 -- tIndex of Names0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the first volume of his extraordinary analysis of the death penalty, Jacques Derrida began a journey toward an ambitious end: the first truly philosophical argument against the death penalty. Exploring an impressive breadth of thought, he traced a deeply entrenched logic throughout the whole of Western philosophy that has justified the state’s right to take a life. He also marked literature as a crucial place where this logic has been most effectively challenged. In this second and final volume, Derrida builds on these analyses toward a definitive argument against capital punishment. Of central importance in this second volume is Kant’s explicit justification of the death penalty in the Metaphysics of Morals. Thoroughly deconstructing Kant’s position—which holds the death penalty as exemplary of the eye-for-an-eye Talionic law—Derrida exposes numerous damning contradictions and exceptions. Keeping the current death penalty in the United States in view, he further explores the “anesthesial logic” he analyzed in volume one, addressing the themes of cruelty and pain through texts by Robespierre and Freud, reading Heidegger, and—in a fascinating, improvised final session—the nineteenth-century Spanish Catholic thinker Donoso Cortés. Ultimately, Derrida shows that the rationality of the death penalty as represented by Kant involves an imposition of knowledge and calculability on a fundamental condition of non-knowledge—that we don’t otherwise know what or when our deaths will be. In this way, the death penalty acts out a phantasm of mastery over one’s own death. Derrida’s thoughts arrive at a particular moment in history: when the death penalty in the United States is the closest it has ever been to abolition, and yet when the arguments on all sides are as confused as ever. His powerful analysis will prove to be a paramount contribution to this debate as well as a lasting entry in his celebrated oeuvre.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCapital punishmentxPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aRottenberg, Elizabeth.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311071193640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226410968423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226410968.jpg  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2